by doubling the patient's dose,

05:00.156 --> 05:02.242
so this got us thinking
that perhaps there's a way

05:02.242 --> 05:05.578
to prevent breakthrough pain
before it even begins,

05:05.578 --> 05:07.539
and, uh, this inspired...

05:10.708 --> 05:12.961
Why start someone
at 10 milligrams

05:12.961 --> 05:16.589
if they really need to start
at 20 milligrams, or even 40?

05:16.589 --> 05:18.716
We don't know the needs
of a specific patient

05:18.716 --> 05:21.177
the way their doctor would,
so we need to let

05:21.177 --> 05:22.762
physicians and nurses know

05:22.762 --> 05:25.265
they need to individualize
the dose.

05:26.808 --> 05:29.102
‐ This is exactly right.

05:29.102 --> 05:30.144
KATHE: Yeah, I agree.

05:30.144 --> 05:32.981
It's very good, Michael.
Very good.

05:32.981 --> 05:34.732
‐ Let's move on it.
‐ Great.

05:34.732 --> 05:36.526
‐ Thank you, everyone.

05:36.526 --> 05:38.152
KATHE: Good work.

05:38.152 --> 05:39.487
‐ [muttering]

05:39.487 --> 05:42.490
Paul, uh, can you stay
for a minute?

05:50.665 --> 05:53.668
I wanna look into launching
