16:38.020 --> 16:41.148
Guy took only four bottles
of OxyContin and nothing else.

16:41.148 --> 16:42.608
I saw a pain clinic in Kentucky

16:42.608 --> 16:43.817
that looked like
a junkie drive‐through.

16:43.817 --> 16:45.027
JERMAINE: What were you doing
in Kentucky?

16:45.027 --> 16:46.320
BRIDGET: It's where
I get my hair done.

16:46.320 --> 16:47.488
‐ The fuck, Bridget?

16:47.488 --> 16:49.323
You could get in serious shit
for this.

16:49.323 --> 16:50.866
‐ Hey, I'm just
making observations

16:50.866 --> 16:52.117
and bringing it
to the appropriate authorities.

16:52.117 --> 16:53.494
‐ Look, I get it, okay?
I get it.

16:53.494 --> 16:54.578
But what's the next move?

16:54.578 --> 16:56.205
‐ You tell me.

16:56.205 --> 16:58.290
‐ Well, if this were cocaine,
you'd try to prevent

16:58.290 --> 17:00.376
the smugglers from bringing
the drugs into the country

17:00.376 --> 17:02.545
and target local dealers
to bust larger syndicates.

17:02.545 --> 17:03.921
Correct?
‐ Correct.

17:03.921 --> 17:06.799
‐ I don't need a sting
operation to find the drugs

17:06.799 --> 17:08.759
because I know
exactly where they are.

17:08.759 --> 17:11.679
BRIDGET: Where?
‐ They're in every pharmacy
in the country.

17:11.679 --> 17:13.013
So I can't call in
the Coast Guard

17:13.013 --> 17:14.014
to protect our borders

17:14.014 --> 17:15.891
because the drugs
are already here.

17:15.891 --> 17:18.269
So who do I bring
a major case against?

17:18.269 --> 17:20.396
Some dickhead with a truck?

17:20.396 --> 17:22.273
A shithole pain clinic
in Kentucky?

17:22.273 --> 17:24.775
‐ I don't know, okay?
I don't know.

17:24.775 --> 17:26.402
But something
is happening here.

17:26.402 --> 17:27.653
A single prescription drug

17:27.653 --> 17:29.697
is filling up jails
in rural areas.

17:29.697 --> 17:31.407
‐ Find me a cartel

17:31.407 --> 17:32.658
and I'll call in
the Coast Guard,

17:32.658 --> 17:35.411
but right now,
this is a local crime issue.

17:37.079 --> 17:40.082
[tense music]

17:40.082 --> 17:47.089
♪ ♪

17:50.217 --> 17:52.344
BRIDGET: Uh, Mr. Wayton?

17:52.344 --> 17:53.929
Bridget Meyer, DEA.
We spoke on the phone.

17:53.929 --> 17:56.307
WAYTON: Yeah. Hey.

17:56.307 --> 17:57.516
‐ What's going on?

17:57.516 --> 17:59.226
WAYTON: We're gonna put in
a higher counter,

17:59.226 --> 18:00.477
tougher to jump over.

18:00.477 --> 18:01.604
Third break‐in this year,

18:01.604 --> 18:03.355
and all they ever take's
the Oxy.

18:03.355 --> 18:05.608
‐ You ever think about
not carrying the pills?

18:05.608 --> 18:08.652
‐ Tried, but they told me
I'd get sued if I did that.

18:08.652 --> 18:10.237
‐ Who told you that?

18:10.237 --> 18:11.447
‐ That woman from Purdue.

18:11.447 --> 18:12.865
‐ What did the Purdue rep say?

18:12.865 --> 18:14.825
WAYTON: She acted like she was
helping me out, you know?

18:14.825 --> 18:17.745
Like she was my good friend
offering advice.

18:17.745 --> 18:20.623
She said if I refused
to dispense her drug,

18:20.623 --> 18:22.791
that doctors and patients
could sue me,

18:22.791 --> 18:24.710
and the lawsuits could
put me out of business.

18:24.710 --> 18:27.421
Either way, I'm screwed.

18:27.421 --> 18:29.632
‐ Do you have her name?

18:29.632 --> 18:32.635
[sinister music]

18:32.635 --> 18:34.928
♪ ♪

18:34.928 --> 18:39.350
[shutter clicking]

18:39.350 --> 18:46.357
♪ ♪

19:02.873 --> 19:04.458
‐ Fuck.
AMBER: No, no, no.

19:04.458 --> 19:06.794
You've got to get
your patients off Vicodin.

19:06.794 --> 19:09.171
I've got one multiple studies
from different pain foundations

19:09.171 --> 19:12.299
that show Vicodin is terrible
for their liver.

19:12.299 --> 19:13.967
Mm‐hmm.

19:13.967 --> 19:16.387
What‐‐I don't have any change.

19:16.387 --> 19:20.015
‐ Bridget Meyer, DEA.
Please exit the car.

19:20.015 --> 19:21.392
‐ I have to call you back.

19:28.607 --> 19:31.318
I'm so sorry
about the change thing.

19:31.318 --> 19:33.320
I get hit up in my car a lot.

19:33.320 --> 19:34.655
‐ I'd like to ask you
some questions

19:34.655 --> 19:37.116
about break‐ins at pharmacies
in the area.

19:37.116 --> 19:38.492
‐ Well, I didn't do it.

19:38.492 --> 19:40.703
I would never risk
scratching my new Manolos.

19:40.703 --> 19:42.996
‐ You're not a suspect, ma'am.

19:42.996 --> 19:45.040
Several of the pharmacists
complained they were told

19:45.040 --> 19:47.459
they had to carry OxyContin
when they didn't want to.

19:47.459 --> 19:49.586
‐ Who told them that?
BRIDGET: They said you did.

19:49.586 --> 19:51.630
They said you threatened them
with lawsuits.

19:51.630 --> 19:53.924
‐ [laughing]
Oh, what?

19:53.924 --> 19:55.467
Oh, you're fucking kidding me.

19:55.467 --> 19:58.470
Um, no. No.
I tried to help them.

19:58.470 --> 20:01.807
I told them doctors
and patients could sue them.

20:01.807 --> 20:04.059
I never said anything
about my company.

20:04.059 --> 20:06.478
‐ Well, they took it
as a threat from you.

20:06.478 --> 20:07.771
They felt
they were being bullied

20:07.771 --> 20:10.065
into carrying a drug
they didn't wanna carry.

20:10.065 --> 20:13.569
‐ Well, I'm not surprised
they were confused.

20:13.569 --> 20:16.155
They're pretty stupid
down here.

20:16.155 --> 20:19.825
That's what happens
when you fuck your sister.

20:19.825 --> 20:21.827
‐ Were you instructed
to threaten these pharmacies

20:21.827 --> 20:24.121
by your employers?

20:24.121 --> 20:26.540
‐ No.

20:26.540 --> 20:27.666
And I have to go.

20:27.666 --> 20:29.251
‐ I just have
a few more questions.

20:29.251 --> 20:30.419
‐ Do I have to answer them
by law?

20:30.419 --> 20:31.962
‐ No, you do not.

20:31.962 --> 20:33.297
‐ [with Southern accent]
Then you have

20:33.297 --> 20:36.341
a great day, ma'am.

20:36.341 --> 20:39.344
[tense music]

20:39.344 --> 20:42.181
♪ ♪

20:42.181 --> 20:45.184
[engine turns over, revs]

20:45.184 --> 20:46.518
[tires squeal]

20:54.318 --> 20:57.321
[gentle orchestral music]

20:57.321 --> 20:59.698
♪ ♪

20:59.698 --> 21:01.450
GUEST: Good to see you.
Thank you for having us.

21:01.450 --> 21:02.701
RICHARD: Oh, of course.
GUEST: Nice to see you.

21:02.701 --> 21:04.161
‐ Glad you could come.

21:04.161 --> 21:05.454
MORTIMER D. A.:
Check out Richard.

21:05.454 --> 21:07.873
I didn't know
he knew how to smile.

21:07.873 --> 21:10.667
‐ It's a smile of relief
he didn't sink the company.

21:10.667 --> 21:13.545
I don't know if I'm happier
we have a potential blockbuster

21:13.545 --> 21:15.839
or annoyed
he actually pulled it off.

21:15.839 --> 21:17.716
‐ Hmm, I heard everyone
at the office hates him.

21:17.716 --> 21:18.926
KATHE: Mm.

21:18.926 --> 21:20.427
Can't stand him.

21:20.427 --> 21:22.429
You know, he didn't even know
what oxycodone was

21:22.429 --> 21:23.680
until I told him,

21:23.680 --> 21:25.599
and now
he micromanages everyone

21:25.599 --> 21:27.309
like he's God's gift
to medicine.

21:27.309 --> 21:30.646
[laughter]

21:35.859 --> 21:37.277
‐ He's gonna make a toast.

21:39.863 --> 21:41.782
MORTIMER: Theresa and I
would like to toast

21:41.782 --> 21:45.452
the opening of the
Sackler Institute at Cornell

21:45.452 --> 21:47.454
as we make our family

21:47.454 --> 21:50.082
the most philanthropic
in America.

21:50.082 --> 21:52.125
[cheers and applause]

21:52.125 --> 21:53.836
RAYMOND: Thank you, Mortimer.

21:53.836 --> 21:57.506
I'd also like to toast
our host, my son, Richard,

21:57.506 --> 22:01.802
for his tireless work on
our latest product, OxyContin.

22:01.802 --> 22:03.387
It's only been out
a few months,

22:03.387 --> 22:05.430
and it's already
a major breakthrough

22:05.430 --> 22:06.932
in pain management.

22:06.932 --> 22:09.184
So to Richard.

22:09.184 --> 22:10.811
ALL: To Richard.

22:10.811 --> 22:12.187
[scattered applause]

22:12.187 --> 22:13.814
BETH: Hi. How are you?

22:13.814 --> 22:16.775
[tense music]

22:16.775 --> 22:18.527
♪ ♪

22:18.527 --> 22:20.237
RICHARD: Your numbers
are good,

22:20.237 --> 22:23.156
but they can be even better.

22:23.156 --> 22:27.411
Just keep pushing your doctors
to individualize the dose,

22:27.411 --> 22:30.289
and I will keep checking in.

22:30.289 --> 22:31.915
Thank you.

22:31.915 --> 22:33.876
Good Unch.

22:33.876 --> 22:36.003
Good boy. Good boy.

22:36.003 --> 22:38.505
‐ Dad hates it when you
bring him into the office.

22:38.505 --> 22:40.966
‐ Then, uh, don't tell him.

22:40.966 --> 22:43.635
‐ Is Unch short for something?

22:43.635 --> 22:45.846
RICHARD: What's going on?

22:45.846 --> 22:47.347
‐ Uh, so...

22:49.099 --> 22:52.060
Uh, Germany isn't gonna work.
‐ Why not?

22:52.060 --> 22:55.230
‐ We have to prove OC has
minimal abuse liability,

22:55.230 --> 22:56.982
and we‐we can't
make that claim.

22:56.982 --> 22:59.860
RICHARD: That's‐that's just
negative thinking.

22:59.860 --> 23:01.904
Can't we run
another long‐term trial

23:01.904 --> 23:03.280
to get more data?

23:03.280 --> 23:05.657
‐ I wasn't aware there were
any long‐term trials.

23:09.995 --> 23:11.371
Dr. Richard,

23:11.371 --> 23:13.999
even if we could get OxyContin
designated uncontrolled,

23:13.999 --> 23:16.585
it's highly likely
it will be abused in Germany

23:16.585 --> 23:18.128
under that classification

23:18.128 --> 23:20.172
and then be reclassified
as controlled.

23:20.172 --> 23:22.507
[slams hands on desk]

23:22.507 --> 23:24.384
RICHARD: God damn it, I'm sick

23:24.384 --> 23:27.387
of all these fucking noes!

23:29.765 --> 23:31.099
I want a yes.

23:31.099 --> 23:32.601
‐ Germany isn't like the U. S.

23:32.601 --> 23:35.145
We can't maneuver
around their laws.

23:35.145 --> 23:37.105
You're wasting a lot of time
on something

23:37.105 --> 23:38.565
that will get revoked.

23:38.565 --> 23:41.276
‐ It's also cultural.
[Richard sighs]

23:41.276 --> 23:43.487
The Germans don't believe
in opioids.

23:43.487 --> 23:46.740
They believe suffering
is part of healing.

23:49.034 --> 23:52.245
JONATHAN: Um, hey, Paul,
will give us a minute?

23:56.041 --> 24:00.379
♪ ♪

24:00.379 --> 24:03.507
Richie.

24:03.507 --> 24:05.342
It's going great.

24:05.342 --> 24:07.386
It really is.

24:07.386 --> 24:09.262
The drug has turned a corner.

24:09.262 --> 24:11.848
We're on an upswing.

24:11.848 --> 24:14.309
You and Beth
should take a trip.

24:14.309 --> 24:15.852
Relax.

24:15.852 --> 24:17.145
You haven't had a break
in years.

24:17.145 --> 24:19.022
Go spend some time
with David and girls.

24:19.022 --> 24:22.776
RICHARD: There's no time
for a break.

24:22.776 --> 24:24.569
There is no break.

24:24.569 --> 24:28.532
There will never be a break.

24:30.659 --> 24:35.956
Look, I‐I know
I can be hard on people,

24:35.956 --> 24:41.211
but can you think
of any greater venture

24:41.211 --> 24:45.007
to help humanity

24:45.007 --> 24:47.634
than curing pain?

24:47.634 --> 24:52.222
We need to get this drug
into Germany.

24:53.724 --> 24:56.476
Please, John, just...

24:56.476 --> 25:00.689
don't give up so fast.

25:00.689 --> 25:03.233
‐ Okay.

25:03.233 --> 25:06.028
Okay. We'll‐we'll keep trying.

25:06.028 --> 25:07.237
‐ Thank you.

25:07.237 --> 25:09.072
FINNIX: We got lucky
with the weather, buddy.

25:09.072 --> 25:11.116
JERRY: No doubt.

25:11.116 --> 25:13.493
FINNIX: It's just nice to get
out and get away from things.

25:13.493 --> 25:15.495
JERRY: Oh, amen.
I could just sit here

25:15.495 --> 25:18.165
and stare at the river,
to be honest.

25:18.165 --> 25:19.958
FINNIX: Pretty crazy world,
these days there.

25:19.958 --> 25:23.712
JERRY: Oh, Lord. Lord.
Oh, it's a mess.

25:23.712 --> 25:26.840
‐ You know, you read about
or heard about

25:26.840 --> 25:29.134
any of these programs

25:29.134 --> 25:32.637
if you think
someone's a homosexual,

25:32.637 --> 25:35.807
they‐‐they're gonna
pray away the gay?

25:35.807 --> 25:37.684
You ever hear of them?

25:37.684 --> 25:39.061
‐ Oh, yeah.
I've heard of that.

25:39.061 --> 25:40.270
FINNIX: Yeah.
‐ Why?

25:40.270 --> 25:42.397
FINNIX: I got a friend up
in Greensboro.

25:42.397 --> 25:46.777
He's thinking
of sending his kid to one.

25:46.777 --> 25:48.862
[scoffs]

25:48.862 --> 25:51.490
JERRY: What, you saying
they don't work or something?

25:51.490 --> 25:54.367
‐ It's snake oil business.

25:54.367 --> 25:57.329
I mean, prayer is good,

25:57.329 --> 26:00.832
but it's not gonna do any more
or less for that

26:00.832 --> 26:02.584
than it would
for anything else.

26:02.584 --> 26:04.628
‐ Well, not to be
a Bible thumper, Doc,

26:04.628 --> 26:06.630
but if you had a kid like that

26:06.630 --> 26:08.924
and you believed
in the good word,

26:08.924 --> 26:11.259
you'd wanna do something to try
to help 'em, wouldn't you?

26:11.259 --> 26:13.762
‐ Yeah, except most all
the research says

26:13.762 --> 26:17.849
that's just, you know,
how people are born.

26:17.849 --> 26:19.476
It's who they are.

26:19.476 --> 26:23.647
‐ Research, huh.
FINNIX: Yeah. Yeah.

26:23.647 --> 26:27.109
‐ I don't know. Maybe.

26:31.321 --> 26:34.616
My cousin's got a kid
who's, uh,

26:34.616 --> 26:38.161
maybe that way.

26:38.161 --> 26:42.124
Just, uh, goes against about
everything he believes in.

26:42.124 --> 26:43.416
‐ Why don't you tell
your cousin

26:43.416 --> 26:45.794
just to‐‐
just think for a minute

26:45.794 --> 26:49.297
about how hard it is
on that kid.

26:49.297 --> 26:55.595
♪ ♪

26:56.596 --> 26:59.808
‐ I don't know
if he can let it go, Doc.

26:59.808 --> 27:01.143
FINNIX: Sure he can.

27:03.103 --> 27:07.232
He can just remind himself
that his love for his kid

27:07.232 --> 27:10.068
is bigger than anything else
in the world.

27:11.570 --> 27:15.240
‐ [chuckles]

27:15.240 --> 27:18.660
He sure does love that kid.

27:18.660 --> 27:20.036
Sure does.

27:21.955 --> 27:24.958
[utensils clattering,
footsteps approaching]

27:24.958 --> 27:31.965
♪ ♪

27:34.759 --> 27:36.094
DIANE: You feeling all right?

27:36.094 --> 27:38.138
‐ Yeah, I'm fine.

27:38.138 --> 27:39.556
Just tired.

27:43.727 --> 27:46.021
DIANE: Well,
you don't have a fever.

27:46.021 --> 27:48.690
Jer, dinner's up.

27:48.690 --> 27:50.233
‐ Mm‐hmm.
[grunts]

27:58.283 --> 28:00.577
DIANE: Bless us, oh Lord,
for these are gifts,

28:00.577 --> 28:03.788
which are boundless,
oh Lord. Amen.

28:03.788 --> 28:06.166
So did you catch anything?

28:06.166 --> 28:10.462
‐ Well, a couple of trout.
Not worth, uh, keeping, though.

28:10.462 --> 28:13.256
‐ And Finnix?
‐ Oh, no.

28:13.256 --> 28:15.926
He wasn't really interested
in fishing.

28:15.926 --> 28:18.220
He seemed, uh, more interested

28:18.220 --> 28:20.138
in talking about
his friend's gay kid.

28:23.308 --> 28:25.352
‐ And why would he do that?

28:25.352 --> 28:28.480
‐ I don't know.
Have to ask him, I guess.

28:28.480 --> 28:30.982
Sure made a big deal
about it, though.

28:30.982 --> 28:34.444
Said how research shows
people are born that way,

28:34.444 --> 28:36.446
so on, so forth.

28:36.446 --> 28:40.033
That's the, uh, city boy
still in him.

28:42.744 --> 28:46.164
‐ He's been here for 40 years.

28:46.164 --> 28:49.167
‐ Well, I guess he ain't
a true believer, then, is he?

28:51.544 --> 28:55.382
The worst thing that, uh,
a parent could hear is that...

28:58.802 --> 29:02.180
Our kid is, um,

29:02.180 --> 29:06.059
queer or gay or lesbian

29:06.059 --> 29:08.228
or whatever they say now.

29:13.817 --> 29:16.111
It'd kill me if you were, Bets.

29:16.111 --> 29:18.029
It'd absolutely kill me.

29:23.326 --> 29:26.913
‐ Well...

29:26.913 --> 29:28.498
I guess you're dead, then.

29:31.501 --> 29:32.877
‐ You got something
to say to me,

29:32.877 --> 29:35.130
or you want old Doc Finnix
to say it for you?

29:35.130 --> 29:37.382
‐ I just said it.

29:37.382 --> 29:39.718
Didn't you hear me?

29:39.718 --> 29:41.386
And what about you?

29:41.386 --> 29:43.013
You hear me this time?!

29:43.013 --> 29:44.347
‐ You don't raise your voice

29:44.347 --> 29:46.224
to your mom in my house,
you hear me?

29:46.224 --> 29:49.311
‐ You don't have
to worry about that,

29:49.311 --> 29:51.313
'cause I'll leave, Dad.

29:51.313 --> 29:53.815
You won't ever have to look
at your queer kid ever again.

29:55.608 --> 29:59.446
‐ Well...

29:59.446 --> 30:00.864
I think that's best.

30:00.864 --> 30:03.116
‐ No!
BETSY: Fine.

30:03.116 --> 30:04.784
I'll leave this weekend.

30:04.784 --> 30:07.078
‐ You do that.
DIANE: No, Jer. No.

30:07.078 --> 30:08.371
You don't have to go anywhere.

30:08.371 --> 30:10.040
‐ No, I do.

30:10.040 --> 30:11.750
I'm not wanted here.

30:11.750 --> 30:14.336
‐ No.
She doesn't have to leave!

30:14.336 --> 30:16.796
I don't care.

30:16.796 --> 30:18.840
I don't care.

30:18.840 --> 30:21.092
I don't care.
I really don't.

30:21.092 --> 30:22.844
Jerry, I don't care.

30:22.844 --> 30:25.847
[sinister music]

30:25.847 --> 30:28.767
♪ ♪

30:28.767 --> 30:30.894
[car door opens]

30:30.894 --> 30:32.020
[car door slams]

30:32.020 --> 30:38.985
♪ ♪

30:44.824 --> 30:47.035
BETSY: Oh, shit. Oh, shit.

30:51.623 --> 30:54.292
[groans]

30:54.292 --> 31:01.299
♪ ♪

31:08.056 --> 31:09.891
EDDIE: Did you check
the methane monitor?

31:17.524 --> 31:20.819
Betsy, did you check
the methane monitor?

31:20.819 --> 31:22.195
‐ Yeah.

31:23.655 --> 31:25.990
[machinery groaning]

31:25.990 --> 31:28.993
Yeah, it's all clear.
It's all clear.

31:30.620 --> 31:33.748
[machine clunks]

31:33.748 --> 31:40.755
♪ ♪

31:46.553 --> 31:48.805
[explosion]

31:48.805 --> 31:50.348
[grunts]

31:50.348 --> 31:52.267
MINER: Help!

31:52.267 --> 31:55.270
[Betsy coughing]

31:56.938 --> 31:58.606
‐ Did you read
the methane monitor?

31:58.606 --> 32:00.150
‐ Of course I did.

32:00.150 --> 32:02.652
[tense music]

32:02.652 --> 32:05.071
How's Eddie?

32:05.071 --> 32:06.406
‐ Go ahead.

32:06.406 --> 32:09.742
‐ They, uh, think he's gonna
lose his right arm.

32:09.742 --> 32:11.828
What was the number?

32:11.828 --> 32:15.123
On the readout,
before the explosion?

32:15.123 --> 32:16.458
‐ Um...

32:16.458 --> 32:18.334
‐ Was it above a four?
‐ No.

32:18.334 --> 32:20.670
When the levels are that high,
the machine just shuts down.

32:20.670 --> 32:22.046
MINING COMPANY REP:
And we both know

32:22.046 --> 32:23.131
it sometimes gets disabled,

32:23.131 --> 32:24.924
which is why
you're there to check it.

32:24.924 --> 32:26.676
‐ Was dust
obscuring the readout?

32:28.261 --> 32:30.555
‐ [moaning softly]

32:30.555 --> 32:32.765
‐ Just‐‐just tell the truth.

32:35.310 --> 32:38.480
‐ Uh...

32:38.480 --> 32:40.023
there might have been.

32:40.023 --> 32:45.236
♪ ♪

32:45.236 --> 32:49.574
‐ Do you realize that men
might be dead 'cause of you?

32:49.574 --> 32:52.368
That it's possible
this mine will close?

32:52.368 --> 32:55.371
Do you know how much damage
you have done?

32:58.625 --> 33:00.376
‐ [crying]
I don't understand.

33:00.376 --> 33:01.961
MINING COMPANY REP: What?
What don't you understand?

33:01.961 --> 33:03.796
‐ I don't‐‐

33:03.796 --> 33:06.174
I don't understand
what's happening to me.

33:12.055 --> 33:14.599
SINGER: ♪ Who's the man
with the master plan?

33:14.599 --> 33:15.934
♪ I'm thinking
of a master plan ♪

33:15.934 --> 33:18.853
‐ Gracias.
PAUL: Hey, I want some of that.

33:18.853 --> 33:20.772
‐ Yeah?
[Paul chuckles]

33:20.772 --> 33:22.065
‐ Oh, it's really good.

33:23.691 --> 33:26.236
‐ Mmm!

33:26.236 --> 33:27.779
‐ You wanna jump in?
[beeper chiming]

33:27.779 --> 33:29.697
PAUL: Yeah, I can do that.
‐ Hold on. Hold on.

33:29.697 --> 33:31.533
Sorry.

33:31.533 --> 33:33.368
‐ This is fucking great.

33:33.368 --> 33:35.995
‐ Um, it's work. Is that okay?
‐ Yeah, go ahead.

33:35.995 --> 33:38.998
No problem.
‐ Okay.

33:38.998 --> 33:40.416
Hello?

33:40.416 --> 33:41.876
WAYTON: Hi. Agent Meyer?

33:41.876 --> 33:44.128
This is Mike Wayton
from Wayton's Pharmacy.

33:44.128 --> 33:45.588
I don't know if you're
still investigating

33:45.588 --> 33:47.173
the guy that broke in here,
but they got him.

33:47.173 --> 33:49.884
‐ Oh.
Where did they catch him?

33:49.884 --> 33:51.553
WAYTON: In his bathtub.

33:51.553 --> 33:54.097
He was dead from an overdose.

33:54.097 --> 33:56.474
His little girl
in the next room.

33:56.474 --> 33:59.352
I tried not to sell that stuff,
but those people‐‐

33:59.352 --> 34:01.521
‐ Um...
PAUL: Bridget!

34:01.521 --> 34:04.148
BRIDGET: I'm‐‐I'm so sorry.
Uh, I‐I gotta go.

34:04.148 --> 34:06.359
Thank you, um...

34:06.359 --> 34:08.444
and I promise you,
it is not your fault.

34:08.444 --> 34:10.071
WAYTON: I appreciate that.

34:10.071 --> 34:13.074
[somber music]

34:13.074 --> 34:20.081
♪ ♪

34:21.082 --> 34:22.834
[cheering]

34:22.834 --> 34:24.669
‐ You want some more?
‐ No, I'm okay.

34:24.669 --> 34:27.672
[hip‐hop music continues]

34:27.672 --> 34:30.800
♪ ♪

34:30.800 --> 34:33.803
[upbeat music over speakers]

34:33.803 --> 34:37.515
♪ ♪

34:37.515 --> 34:40.560
PAUL: You, uh, want
to stop here, take a look?

34:40.560 --> 34:42.812
Yeah, right here.

34:42.812 --> 34:45.815
[soft dramatic music]

34:45.815 --> 34:49.569
♪ ♪

34:49.569 --> 34:53.364
‐ How many kids in your school
are on OxyContin?

34:53.364 --> 34:54.616
‐ Maybe half.

34:54.616 --> 35:01.623
♪ ♪

35:03.124 --> 35:06.336
PAUL: Bridget.

35:06.336 --> 35:07.378
Down here.
‐ Oh.

35:07.378 --> 35:09.172
Are you okay?
‐ Yeah, I'm fine.

35:09.172 --> 35:12.050
Uh, I know we've only been
dating for nine months,

35:12.050 --> 35:15.595
but I have never
been with someone

35:15.595 --> 35:18.598
that I respected

35:18.598 --> 35:22.060
and admired and cared for

35:22.060 --> 35:26.981
and loved
as much as I love you.

35:26.981 --> 35:29.651
You're my hero,

35:29.651 --> 35:34.113
and I would be so honored

35:34.113 --> 35:37.450
if you would be my‐‐my wife.

35:37.450 --> 35:39.327
‐ Oh, my God.
[Paul chuckles]

35:39.327 --> 35:41.037
‐ Yes?
BRIDGET: Yes!

35:41.037 --> 35:43.206
Yes! I'm sorry. I'm so sorry.
[Paul laughs]

35:43.206 --> 35:45.166
‐ Don't apologize. Here. Wait.
‐ Oh, my God!

35:45.166 --> 35:48.586
[upbeat music continues]

35:48.586 --> 35:50.838
PAUL: You think you got it?
‐ Wait, I got it. Oh, my God!

35:50.838 --> 35:52.131
[both laugh]

35:52.131 --> 35:54.092
Oh, my gosh!

35:56.010 --> 35:57.053
[knocks on door]

35:57.887 --> 36:00.056
‐ [inaudible]
‐ Okay.

36:00.056 --> 36:01.683
‐ You asked to speak
to me, sir?

36:05.353 --> 36:07.939
‐ Stay out
of Diversion's domain.

36:07.939 --> 36:10.525
You made a presentation,
and we listened.

36:10.525 --> 36:12.360
But in no way did this
give you the right

36:12.360 --> 36:14.570
to start
an independent investigation.

36:14.570 --> 36:16.030
‐ I understand, sir.

36:16.030 --> 36:18.574
And I immediately gave
everything I uncovered

36:18.574 --> 36:22.328
to Diversion,
but I believe we must pursue.

36:22.328 --> 36:23.329
‐ Why?

36:23.329 --> 36:25.206
‐ Agent Spellman told me

36:25.206 --> 36:27.750
that the reason we can't pursue
an OxyContin case

36:27.750 --> 36:30.670
is that there is no cartel
to go after.

36:30.670 --> 36:32.088
The drug is here legally

36:32.088 --> 36:33.965
and opioids are now
widely accepted

36:33.965 --> 36:35.925
in the medical community.

36:35.925 --> 36:38.386
But I believe
I found the cartel.

36:38.386 --> 36:40.012
‐ Oh, you have?
BRIDGET: Yes, sir.

36:40.012 --> 36:41.514
I even have their address.

36:41.514 --> 36:45.017
201 Tresser Boulevard,
Stamford, Connecticut.

36:45.017 --> 36:47.311
That's the main headquarters
of Purdue Pharma.

36:47.311 --> 36:49.147
They are the makers
of OxyContin,

36:49.147 --> 36:51.524
and they are the cartel, sir.

36:51.524 --> 36:53.484
They are lying to doctors
and patients

36:53.484 --> 36:56.154
about the dangers of the drug,
and they are forcing pharmacies

36:56.154 --> 36:58.406
to carry it with threats
of lawsuits if they don't.

36:58.406 --> 37:00.867
And the FDA is
an unwitting coconspirator

37:00.867 --> 37:02.994
because they issued Purdue
a warning label

37:02.994 --> 37:05.955
that gives them cover to say
that the drug is less addictive

37:05.955 --> 37:09.625
than other opioids
when it's clearly not.

37:09.625 --> 37:12.170
‐ Could the FDA be colluding
with Purdue?

37:12.170 --> 37:14.172
BRIDGET: It's possible.

37:14.172 --> 37:17.300
The individual who approved
this highly unusual wording

37:17.300 --> 37:20.344
on the warning label
now works for Purdue.

37:20.344 --> 37:21.763
‐ Really?
BRIDGET: Yes, sir.

37:21.763 --> 37:24.849
Curtis Wright.
We need to act now.

37:24.849 --> 37:27.727
We have to go after
Purdue Pharma now, sir.

37:27.727 --> 37:28.811
Right now.

37:28.811 --> 37:31.647
[tense music]

37:31.647 --> 37:33.065
[Moore clears throat]

37:33.065 --> 37:36.444
MOORE: How attached are you
to your service pistol?

37:36.444 --> 37:37.945
‐ Why do you ask?

37:37.945 --> 37:42.617
‐ Diversion agents aren't
allowed to carry firearms.

37:42.617 --> 37:44.368
‐ Are you transferring me?

37:44.368 --> 37:46.329
‐ No.

37:46.329 --> 37:48.873
No, I'm promoting you.

37:48.873 --> 37:50.583
I'd like you to be
deputy director

37:50.583 --> 37:52.543
of the diversion division.

37:52.543 --> 37:54.837
They need someone with balls
over there.

37:57.006 --> 37:58.674
‐ I accept.

37:58.674 --> 38:01.302
‐ [chuckles]

38:01.302 --> 38:03.554
Congratulations, Bridget.

38:03.554 --> 38:05.389
I believe you're now
the highest ranking woman

38:05.389 --> 38:08.559
in the DEA.

38:08.559 --> 38:09.727
‐ Thank you.

38:09.727 --> 38:11.020
RANDY: Oh, hey, Doc.

38:11.020 --> 38:13.439
This is Rick Mountcastle,
U. S. Attorney's office.

38:13.439 --> 38:15.358
See, uh, we wanna ask you
a few questions

38:15.358 --> 38:17.693
about a case
that we're working on.

38:17.693 --> 38:19.111
‐ Sure.

38:19.111 --> 38:21.697
‐ So Randy described a scenario
in which his nurse

38:21.697 --> 38:24.408
was quite forceful
about him taking OxyContin.

38:24.408 --> 38:25.743
Is that standard?

38:25.743 --> 38:27.078
‐ What do you mean?

38:27.078 --> 38:28.538
‐ I mean, is there
some sort of hospital policy

38:28.538 --> 38:31.958
to push OxyContin?

38:31.958 --> 38:34.418
‐ The hospital can now get sued
if the patient felt

38:34.418 --> 38:36.796
that we didn't manage
their pain properly.

38:36.796 --> 38:38.840
Or they can write us
a bad review online,

38:38.840 --> 38:42.051
which would cause the staff
to be rebuked by management.

38:42.051 --> 38:44.554
Nurses have been fired
over online reviews.

38:44.554 --> 38:46.305
‐ Is that just this hospital?

38:46.305 --> 38:48.891
‐ No. All across the country.

38:48.891 --> 38:50.476
Internet has really
changed things.

38:50.476 --> 38:52.144
‐ Online reviews
have caused a shift

38:52.144 --> 38:54.355
in national opioid prescribing?

38:54.355 --> 38:58.192
♪ ♪

38:58.192 --> 39:00.611
‐ How are you feeling?

39:00.611 --> 39:02.363
‐ I'm a little better.

39:02.363 --> 39:04.407
I appreciate it, Doc.
Thank you.

39:04.407 --> 39:07.159
‐ All right.
Well, I'll check back in.

39:10.705 --> 39:13.416
The older nurses hate it.

39:13.416 --> 39:14.667
All the opioids.

39:20.298 --> 39:23.009
‐ I wanted to show you this.

39:23.009 --> 39:25.970
Pain societies have
infiltrated the hospital rooms,

39:25.970 --> 39:28.598
and they love their pamphlets.

39:28.598 --> 39:31.642
I never heard that phrase
before today,

39:31.642 --> 39:33.519
and now it's everywhere I look.

39:36.814 --> 39:39.734
ROGER: Thank you all
for coming.

39:39.734 --> 39:42.570
I'm Roger Thurby from the
Appalachian Pain Foundation.

39:42.570 --> 39:45.615
We're here tonight to discuss
opioids in our community.

39:45.615 --> 39:47.658
We know they've been getting
a lot of attention lately

39:47.658 --> 39:51.287
and there's been some folks
struggling with addiction,

39:51.287 --> 39:54.123
so we decided to gather experts
on the situation

39:54.123 --> 39:55.541
and discuss it publicly.

39:55.541 --> 39:57.168
First, I'd like
to turn the microphone over

39:57.168 --> 39:59.503
to Ms. Barbara Mullins,
who's on the editorial board

39:59.503 --> 40:00.963
of the "Journal of Pain."

40:00.963 --> 40:03.257
BARBARA: Thank y'all
for having me here tonight.

40:03.257 --> 40:05.676
Opioid abuse is
certainly growing,

40:05.676 --> 40:08.971
but it's important
to distinguish between abusers

40:08.971 --> 40:11.766
and legitimate pain patients
who need these medicines.

40:11.766 --> 40:13.601
ROGER: So is this a consensus?

40:13.601 --> 40:16.520
Pills aren't the issue,
it's the addicts abusing them?

40:16.520 --> 40:19.231
‐ Absolutely, but I also
think it's important

40:19.231 --> 40:21.317
the pharmaceutical industry
does a better job

40:21.317 --> 40:22.693
working with law enforcement

40:22.693 --> 40:25.488
to keep these products
out of the hands of abusers.

40:25.488 --> 40:28.240
They have some responsibility
here too.

40:28.240 --> 40:29.951
‐ Uh, my sciatica was so bad

40:29.951 --> 40:31.994
I couldn't even get up
in the morning.

40:31.994 --> 40:34.580
And right when I finally
get back to normal,

40:34.580 --> 40:36.540
I'm terrified my drugs
are gonna be pulled

40:36.540 --> 40:37.959
'cause of these junkies.

40:37.959 --> 40:39.251
DONALD: Absolutely not, ma'am.

40:39.251 --> 40:40.586
We are doing everything
in our power

40:40.586 --> 40:42.088
to make sure
you get your medication.

40:42.088 --> 40:45.841
[applause]

40:45.841 --> 40:48.052
ROGER: Yes, sir, in the back.
‐ Hi.

40:48.052 --> 40:50.554
Um, I've been hearing
from some folks

40:50.554 --> 40:52.473
the real problem is,
OxyContin is

40:52.473 --> 40:55.977
much more addictive
than its maker claims.

40:55.977 --> 40:58.980
‐ Is there any truth to that?
‐ No, it's a misconception.

40:58.980 --> 41:00.606
Vicodin is actually
being abused

41:00.606 --> 41:02.692
at a much higher rate
of its total sales.

41:02.692 --> 41:04.110
BARBARA: That's right.
Much higher.

41:04.110 --> 41:07.113
And actually, Vicodin is
potentially bad for your liver.

41:07.113 --> 41:08.823
I personally wouldn't use it.

41:08.823 --> 41:10.032
‐ I wouldn't either.

41:10.032 --> 41:11.575
It has addictive qualities,

41:11.575 --> 41:15.162
whereas less than 1% of people
become addicted to OxyContin.

41:15.162 --> 41:18.165
[crowd muttering]

41:22.378 --> 41:25.339
‐ Hey. How you feeling?
‐ I'm good. I'm good.

41:25.339 --> 41:27.466
How y'all doing?
‐ Good. We missed ya.

41:27.466 --> 41:28.759
Hey, the guys are
in the conference room.

41:28.759 --> 41:30.428
RANDY: Get in here and talk
to these maniacs.

41:30.428 --> 41:33.014
‐ Pain Society has been
pushing them for years,

41:33.014 --> 41:37.393
and once pain became accepted
as the fifth vital sign, yeah,

41:37.393 --> 41:40.062
J‐Co went from anti‐opioid
to pro‐opioid.

41:40.062 --> 41:42.231
‐ Hey, Gregg!
GREGG: Hey.

41:42.231 --> 41:45.151
‐ Conversation sounded like
a barrel of laughs.

41:45.151 --> 41:47.069
Mind if I grab a sarsaparilla
and join y'all?

41:47.069 --> 41:48.154
‐ [chuckles]

41:48.154 --> 41:49.405
Brother,
when you said one week,

41:49.405 --> 41:51.240
you really meant it.

41:51.240 --> 41:53.701
‐ Randy, how are you feeling?

41:53.701 --> 41:55.703
‐ I think I just might be
in the clear.

41:55.703 --> 41:57.121
Everything's negative.

41:57.121 --> 41:59.665
‐ That's wonderful news.

41:59.665 --> 42:04.003
‐ So what have we got
on these pain foundations?

42:04.003 --> 42:05.171
Totally legit, right?

42:05.171 --> 42:07.673
Just a bunch
of straight shooters.

42:07.673 --> 42:10.843
‐ Yeah.
Humanitarians of the year.

42:10.843 --> 42:13.095
Uh, started with the
Appalachian Pain Foundation.

42:13.095 --> 42:17.141
Pulled their tax returns,
and you were spot‐on, Rick.

42:17.141 --> 42:20.478
In 2000, they got a $20,000
grant from Purdue Pharma

42:20.478 --> 42:24.190
to literally start
their organization.

42:24.190 --> 42:26.275
‐ [scoffs]
What tipped you off?

42:26.275 --> 42:27.610
‐ When they were
pushing OxyContin

42:27.610 --> 42:30.613
and trashing Vicodin.

42:30.613 --> 42:31.739
‐ Subtle.

42:31.739 --> 42:33.199
‐ Did you find
Purdue connections

42:33.199 --> 42:36.619
with other pain societies?

42:36.619 --> 42:40.206
‐ Gentlemen,
it is time to buckle up.

42:41.916 --> 42:43.501
RICK: The American
Pain Society claims

42:43.501 --> 42:45.086
to be
an independent medical group

42:45.086 --> 42:47.296
representing physician
pain specialists,

42:47.296 --> 42:49.298
but it receives a sizable
portion of its funding

42:49.298 --> 42:50.633
from the drug industry,

42:50.633 --> 42:53.803
including significant grants
from Purdue Pharma,

42:53.803 --> 42:55.554
who are one
of the biggest beneficiaries

42:55.554 --> 42:57.890
of the society's
successful effort

42:57.890 --> 43:01.102
to make pain
the fifth vital sign.

43:01.102 --> 43:03.020
Purdue also spent heavily

43:03.020 --> 43:05.773
to subsidize the American
Academy of Pain Medicine

43:05.773 --> 43:07.566
and, in 1997,

43:07.566 --> 43:11.695
spent $500,000 to underwrite
the work of a joint committee

43:11.695 --> 43:14.824
formed by these two groups,
which issued a report

43:14.824 --> 43:17.952
urging the broader use
of powerful narcotics.

43:17.952 --> 43:21.163
Now, Purdue also
contributed generously

43:21.163 --> 43:22.873
to patient advocacy groups,

43:22.873 --> 43:25.584
like the National Foundation
for the Treatment of Pain

43:25.584 --> 43:28.462
and the American
Chronic Pain Association,

43:28.462 --> 43:31.048
but in effect, they helped fund

43:31.048 --> 43:33.592
an entire network
of pain groups

43:33.592 --> 43:36.637
that represented themselves
as independent,

43:36.637 --> 43:40.766
but all heavily promoted
the use of opioids.

43:40.766 --> 43:42.643
Uh, permission to approach
the bench, Your Honor?

43:45.563 --> 43:48.190
Now, you might recognize
this pain chart,

43:48.190 --> 43:51.694
as, uh, it's in hospital rooms
and doctor's offices

43:51.694 --> 43:53.154
all across the country.

43:53.154 --> 43:55.447
It's from the organization
Partners Against Pain,

43:55.447 --> 43:57.283
which is ostensibly
an educational alliance

43:57.283 --> 43:59.869
dedicated to the treatment
of pain,

43:59.869 --> 44:01.662
but, in fact,

44:01.662 --> 44:03.789
it is fully funded and run
by Purdue Pharma.

44:03.789 --> 44:08.085
It is 100% Purdue‐owned.

44:08.085 --> 44:10.504
In effect,
it's Purdue's shadow company,

44:10.504 --> 44:12.131
which has infiltrated

44:12.131 --> 44:15.509
hospital rooms
and doctor's offices

44:15.509 --> 44:18.762
as a stealth tool
to prompt pain discussions

44:18.762 --> 44:20.806
between doctors, nurses,
and patients

44:20.806 --> 44:22.474
with the goal
of prescribing more opioids‐‐

44:22.474 --> 44:25.269
‐ Objection. Conjecture.

44:25.269 --> 44:27.104
Purdue has never hidden
its relationship

44:27.104 --> 44:28.480
with Partners Against Pain.

44:28.480 --> 44:30.399
‐ Then why not put Purdue
Pharma on these pain charts

44:30.399 --> 44:31.525
instead of
a different company name?

44:31.525 --> 44:34.236
PURDUE LAWYER: Your Honor, th‐‐

44:34.236 --> 44:35.988
‐ Proceed.

44:35.988 --> 44:38.949
RICK: Partners Against Pain
also has a website

44:38.949 --> 44:41.785
masquerading
as a patient advocacy group

44:41.785 --> 44:44.705
to guide pain sufferers
to specialists,

44:44.705 --> 44:46.624
but every specialist
that it sends you to

44:46.624 --> 44:50.586
is a doctor with a very high
rate of prescribing OxyContin.

44:50.586 --> 44:52.963
So pain societies
partially or fully funded

44:52.963 --> 44:55.841
by Purdue Pharma and other
pharmaceutical companies

44:55.841 --> 44:59.929
are de facto propaganda
divisions for big pharma.

44:59.929 --> 45:04.099
The deception is so effective
that some sales reps at Purdue

45:04.099 --> 45:06.852
thought they were using
independent data

45:06.852 --> 45:09.230
when they were quoting studies
from the American Pain Society

45:09.230 --> 45:12.691
with slogans like, "Pain is
the fifth vital sign."

45:12.691 --> 45:15.486
And, of course,
the solution for pain

45:15.486 --> 45:20.991
is always, always
an increased use of opioids.

45:20.991 --> 45:23.494
And it's an increase so high
in the last five years

45:23.494 --> 45:25.287
it's at levels not seen

45:25.287 --> 45:30.042
since the run‐up to the
Harrison Narcotics Tax Act...

45:30.042 --> 45:32.044
of 1914.

45:34.046 --> 45:35.256
Thank you, Your Honor.

45:35.256 --> 45:38.259
[dramatic music]

45:38.259 --> 45:39.718
♪ ♪

45:39.718 --> 45:42.513
‐ Permission granted
to release requested documents

45:42.513 --> 45:46.558
relating to marketing,
research, and distribution.

45:48.686 --> 45:51.188
‐ All right.

45:54.358 --> 45:57.569
Go get 'em, Boss.
‐ [chuckles]

45:57.569 --> 46:00.739
‐ I know you all are dying
to know the results

46:00.739 --> 46:02.199
of the Toppers Contest.

46:02.199 --> 46:05.244
[cheers and applause]

46:05.244 --> 46:07.997
All right, but before
I name the winner,

46:07.997 --> 46:09.581
I just have to say

46:09.581 --> 46:12.710
what an incredible quarter
you had.

46:12.710 --> 46:15.629
"Individualize the Dose"
got a huge number of doctors

46:15.629 --> 46:18.299
to start at 20 milligrams,
and some at even 40!

46:18.299 --> 46:20.009
You guys fucking rock!

46:20.009 --> 46:23.012
[cheers and applause]

46:23.971 --> 46:28.684
All right, but there can
only be one winner.

46:28.684 --> 46:32.354
And this quarter, it is...

46:32.354 --> 46:33.647
Todd Brunward.

46:33.647 --> 46:35.941
‐ Fuck yeah! Come on!

46:35.941 --> 46:37.026
MARTIN: All right.
All right.

46:37.026 --> 46:39.486
Todd, Todd sold

46:39.486 --> 46:44.033
$767,000 worth of OxyContin,

46:44.033 --> 46:46.452
one of the highest
in the nation.

46:46.452 --> 46:48.412
Todd, come up here.

46:48.412 --> 46:50.748
Tell everybody how you did it.

46:50.748 --> 46:55.252
‐ Um, well, you know,
it was all hustle

46:55.252 --> 46:57.087
and determination.

46:57.087 --> 47:00.299
Yeah, I went to every doctor
on my IMS sheet

47:00.299 --> 47:03.510
and, uh, told them
what we got here.

47:03.510 --> 47:06.764
AMBER: He's such a liar.
He didn't hustle shit.

47:06.764 --> 47:08.974
‐ What do you mean?
‐ He has a whale.

47:08.974 --> 47:10.559
One doctor running a pill mill.

47:10.559 --> 47:12.019
‐ What's a pill mill?

47:12.019 --> 47:14.521
‐ It's a doctor
who overprescribes like crazy.

47:14.521 --> 47:16.607
It's a total gold mine
if you can land one.

47:16.607 --> 47:18.192
Todd works a few hours a month,

47:18.192 --> 47:21.070
then plays video games
and smokes pot all day.

47:21.070 --> 47:23.405
It is so unfair
that he wins with a pill mill.

47:23.405 --> 47:24.740
‐ Yeah.

47:24.740 --> 47:27.409
Shouldn't he report a doctor
for something like that?

47:27.409 --> 47:30.621
‐ He'd probably get fired
if he reported him.

47:30.621 --> 47:32.790
‐ So Purdue want whales?

47:32.790 --> 47:34.958
‐ Oh, sure.

47:34.958 --> 47:36.835
You don't wanna
shut a whale down.

47:36.835 --> 47:37.920
You wanna reel it in.

47:37.920 --> 47:40.923
[tense music]

47:40.923 --> 47:43.217
♪ ♪

47:43.217 --> 47:44.927
BARBARA: Sam.
‐ Hey.

47:44.927 --> 47:47.554
[both laugh]
BARBARA: Oh!

47:47.554 --> 47:50.849
Oh, I can't tell you
how happy I am to see you.

47:50.849 --> 47:53.310
It's been way too long.
FINNIX: Way too long.

47:53.310 --> 47:54.978
‐ Yeah, you look wonderful.

47:54.978 --> 47:57.314
‐ Oh, come on.
‐ What'd you do?

47:57.314 --> 47:59.483
[both laugh]

47:59.483 --> 48:02.111
I sometimes think about you
all holed up in that house

48:02.111 --> 48:03.821
and it just breaks my heart.

48:03.821 --> 48:05.656
It's not
what Shelly would want.

48:05.656 --> 48:07.074
‐ Well, it's her fault.

48:07.074 --> 48:09.034
She's the one that dragged me
down to the mountains.

48:09.034 --> 48:11.161
BARBARA: Yeah, but she knew
you'd follow her.

48:11.161 --> 48:13.539
‐ [chuckles]
Yeah, she did.

48:16.041 --> 48:19.086
‐ Do you ever regret it?
‐ Regret what?

48:19.086 --> 48:21.880
BARBARA: Spending all
those years in Appalachia?

48:21.880 --> 48:24.675
Top of your class at Duke,
a fellowship at Johns Hopkins.

48:24.675 --> 48:26.510
[laughs]
It's pretty heady stuff.

48:26.510 --> 48:30.139
‐ Yeah. That's pretty good.
‐ Yeah.

48:30.139 --> 48:31.765
‐ No.

48:31.765 --> 48:33.725
I like it down there.

48:33.725 --> 48:38.605
Yeah, I mean, it's not exactly
the life I had planned,

48:38.605 --> 48:41.900
but it's been good.

48:41.900 --> 48:44.987
It's good.

48:44.987 --> 48:48.323
Until your sister left.

48:48.323 --> 48:49.741
‐ I miss her too.

48:52.369 --> 48:55.747
But you got
a lot of years still.

48:55.747 --> 48:57.499
FINNIX: Uh, yeah.

48:57.499 --> 48:59.626
That's kinda...

48:59.626 --> 49:02.671
kinda why I wanted
to come up here

49:02.671 --> 49:04.381
and visit with you, Barbara.

49:05.924 --> 49:08.552
Uh...

49:08.552 --> 49:12.723
You know, this whole idea

49:12.723 --> 49:16.393
of, uh, dating again,

49:16.393 --> 49:20.814
I mean, it's really, you know,
odd just saying dating.

49:20.814 --> 49:23.192
But...

49:23.192 --> 49:25.611
I don't know.

49:25.611 --> 49:29.323
First of all,
it makes me feel...

49:29.323 --> 49:31.283
guilty.

49:31.283 --> 49:36.163
Like I'm doing wrong by Shelly,
you know?

49:36.163 --> 49:38.457
‐ What, did you meet someone?

49:38.457 --> 49:40.626
‐ I don't know.

49:40.626 --> 49:41.919
Maybe.

49:41.919 --> 49:43.754
BARBARA: Aww.

49:43.754 --> 49:47.132
Sam, if you spend
the rest of your life

49:47.132 --> 49:48.217
locked away in that house,

49:48.217 --> 49:49.885
you will be doing
a great disservice

49:49.885 --> 49:51.595
to that spitfire you married.

49:54.556 --> 49:57.559
[soft music]

49:57.559 --> 50:04.566
♪ ♪

50:06.193 --> 50:08.111
‐ But is it really okay?

50:10.906 --> 50:15.285
‐ You're using your pain
as an excuse not to live.

50:17.496 --> 50:19.873
But it's time
to start living again.

50:19.873 --> 50:26.880
♪ ♪

50:45.691 --> 50:47.609
[phone beeps]

50:47.609 --> 50:50.362
[line trilling]

50:50.362 --> 50:51.947
DREA: Hello?
‐ Hey.

50:51.947 --> 50:53.574
‐ Well, be still my heart.

50:53.574 --> 50:55.367
Is this my knight
in shining armor?

50:55.367 --> 50:58.161
‐ Oh, well, yeah, I guess.
[chuckles nervously]

50:58.161 --> 51:00.289
‐ Please tell me
I'm gonna see you in Orlando

51:00.289 --> 51:01.331
in a few weeks.

51:01.331 --> 51:03.667
‐ Yeah, well, uh,

51:03.667 --> 51:05.210
actually,
that's why I'm calling.

51:05.210 --> 51:08.505
I, you know, wanted to know
if, uh, you still wanted me to.

51:08.505 --> 51:11.800
DREA: Well, of course, I do.
‐ Well, good. Good.

51:11.800 --> 51:13.969
‐ Yes, and you're gonna
make another speech,

51:13.969 --> 51:15.971
and you're gonna
get paid for it this time.

51:15.971 --> 51:17.306
Bring your swim trunks.

51:17.306 --> 51:19.182
‐ [chuckles]
Oh, all right.

51:19.182 --> 51:21.393
Well, I don't know if‐‐
not sure I got any,

51:21.393 --> 51:23.395
but I'll, uh‐‐I'll swing by
and pick some up.

51:23.395 --> 51:24.479
[line beeps]

51:24.479 --> 51:26.315
Hey, can you‐‐
I'm gonna call you‐‐

51:26.315 --> 51:27.316
call you a little later.

51:27.316 --> 51:28.942
I gotta take this call here.

51:28.942 --> 51:31.236
DREA: Yes. All right.
See you Wednesday.

51:31.236 --> 51:33.196
‐ All right.
Looking forward to it.

51:33.196 --> 51:34.656
[phone beeps]
Hello?

51:34.656 --> 51:36.325
LEAH: Dr. Finnix,
where are you?

51:36.325 --> 51:39.286
‐ I'm in D.C.
I'm visiting Shelly's sister.

51:39.286 --> 51:40.787
LEAH: Well,
you gotta come back.

51:40.787 --> 51:43.457
There was an explosion
at the mine.

51:43.457 --> 51:45.125
‐ How‐‐how bad?

51:45.125 --> 51:46.335
LEAH: Everyone's alive,

51:46.335 --> 51:47.586
but a bunch
are at the hospital.

51:47.586 --> 51:49.296
Betsy Mallum is in bad shape.

51:49.296 --> 51:51.381
‐ Okay. All right.
I'm on my way.

51:52.716 --> 51:53.717
[engine turns over]

51:53.717 --> 51:56.720
[eerie music]

51:56.720 --> 52:03.727
♪ ♪

52:18.575 --> 52:20.369
[truck door slams]

52:20.369 --> 52:23.246
‐ Morning.
DRIVER: Morning.

52:23.246 --> 52:25.540
‐ Big truck
for just a couple boxes.

52:28.251 --> 52:32.673
♪ ♪

52:32.673 --> 52:34.466
‐ They're drowning us
in paperwork.

52:34.466 --> 52:37.386
‐ This isn't half of it.

52:40.222 --> 52:41.848
‐ Oh, Lord.

52:44.768 --> 52:45.894
‐ It's gonna take us
over a year

52:45.894 --> 52:47.270
just to catalog all this.

52:47.270 --> 52:50.148
‐ And they'll keep
selling pills the entire time.

52:50.148 --> 52:56.571
♪ ♪

52:57.781 --> 53:01.034
‐ So we've been talking
to the German regulators,

53:01.034 --> 53:04.413
and we just keep hitting
a brick wall.

53:04.413 --> 53:05.914
Why did you have to pick

53:05.914 --> 53:08.208
the hardest country
in the world

53:08.208 --> 53:09.751
to get a drug uncontrolled?

53:15.173 --> 53:16.383
‐ Follow me.

53:19.553 --> 53:23.056
I'm, uh, sorry to bother you,
but would you mind giving me

53:23.056 --> 53:25.100
a few minutes alone
with my brother?

53:47.330 --> 53:52.085
The reason why I want to get
relaxed status in Germany

53:52.085 --> 53:56.006
is precisely because

53:56.006 --> 54:00.302
they do have the strictest
regulations in Europe.

54:00.302 --> 54:02.679
If we get Germany uncontrolled,

54:02.679 --> 54:05.766
even if the status
is eventually revoked,

54:05.766 --> 54:09.895
it will serve as a gateway
to the rest of Europe,

54:09.895 --> 54:14.232
which will then open us up to
the majority of global markets.

54:14.232 --> 54:17.402
[dramatic music]

54:17.402 --> 54:20.947
No one in the history
of this family

54:20.947 --> 54:22.199
will ever come close

54:22.199 --> 54:24.201
to accomplishing
what we're gonna do.

54:28.121 --> 54:32.292
We're going to cure the world
of its pain.

54:34.878 --> 54:37.881
‐ [breathing heavily]

54:44.012 --> 54:46.264
‐ So unfortunately,
the x‐rays show

54:46.264 --> 54:47.933
you've got four broken ribs.

54:47.933 --> 54:51.144
‐ Yeah. I saw it there.

54:51.144 --> 54:52.813
Thank you very much, Doc.

54:52.813 --> 54:54.648
‐ Uh, Dr. Finnix,
please don't rush.

54:54.648 --> 54:56.566
This is a real injury.
FINNIX: I know.

54:56.566 --> 54:58.026
[exhales]
I know, yeah.

54:58.026 --> 55:00.695
I'm just in a little bit
of a hurry here.

55:00.695 --> 55:04.241
‐ On a scale of one to ten,
how would you rate your pain?

55:04.241 --> 55:05.367
‐ What is that?

55:05.367 --> 55:06.868
I don't have my, uh‐‐
my readers.

55:06.868 --> 55:08.662
DOCTOR:
It's a pain assessment chart.

55:08.662 --> 55:10.789
FINNIX: Oh, I've never seen
one of those.

55:10.789 --> 55:13.542
I don't know.

55:13.542 --> 55:16.169
Five, six. Call it a five.
I don't know.

55:16.169 --> 55:17.587
DOCTOR: All right.

55:17.587 --> 55:21.424
I'm gonna start you
at 20 milligrams of OxyContin.

55:21.424 --> 55:23.426
‐ 20?

55:23.426 --> 55:26.555
I usually start my patients
at, uh, 10.

55:26.555 --> 55:28.598
‐ Well, I like
to individualize the dose.

55:28.598 --> 55:31.601
[ominous music]

55:31.601 --> 55:37.023
♪ ♪
